kenStream<Unit> member to access tokens from the tokenization phase\n- **Implementation**: At line 955-1017 in BytecodeCompiler.cpp, ScriptCompiler<Unit>::compile() calls parser->globalBody() or parser->evalBody() to parse source into a ParseNode\n\n### 4. AST Representation: ParseNode (js/src/frontend/ParseNode.h/cpp)\nThe parser produces an Abstract Syntax Tree composed of ParseNode objects:\n- **Base Class**: ParseNode is the base class for all AST nodes\n- **Node Types**: Various specialized subclasses represent different language constructs:\n  - BinaryNode - Binary operators (e.g., addition, assignment)\n  - UnaryNode - Unary operators (e.g., negation, typeof)\n  - ListNode - Lists of items (arrays, arguments, statements)\n  - CallNode - Function calls\n  - FunctionNode - Function declarations/expressions\n  - PropertyAccess, PropertyByValue - Member access\n  - And many more for control flow, literals, etc.\n- **AST Definition Table**: js/src/jsast.tbl contains the canonical list of all AST node types (AST_PROGRAM, AST_IDENTIFIER, AST_BINARY_EXPR, etc.) used for reflection and introspection\n- **Lifetime**: All ParseNode instances are allocated in a LifoAlloc (Last-In-First-Out allocator) in the context's memory arena and are bulk-deallocated when parsing completes\n\n### 5. Shared Compilation Context: SharedContext (js/src/frontend/SharedContext.h)\nThe SharedContext class maintains information needed by both the parser and bytecode emitter:\n- Contains scope information (global, eval, function scopes)\n- Tracks directives like \"use strict\" and \"use asm\"\n- Maintains binding information\n- Includes specialized subclasses: GlobalSharedContext, EvalSharedContext, ModuleSharedContext, and FunctionBox\n\n### 6. Bytecode Emission: BytecodeEmitter (js/src/frontend/BytecodeEmitter.h/cpp)\nOnce parsing completes successfully, the BytecodeEmitter converts the AST into bytecode:\n- **Main Method**: emitScript(ParseNode* body) - Takes the root ParseNode from parsing and generates bytecode\n- **Implementation**: Located at line 525 in BytecodeEmitter.h\n- **Process**: The emitter traverses the AST and emits JSOp bytecode instructions and associated metadata\n- **Bytecode Sections**: Uses BytecodeSection (js/src/frontend/BytecodeSection.h) to manage separate prologue and main bytecode sections\n- **Helper Emitters**: Includes specialized emitter classes for specific constructs:\n  - CallOrNewEmitter - Function calls and new expressions\n  - ForOfEmitter, ForInEmitter - Loop constructs\n  - TryEmitter, SwitchEmitter - Control flow\n  - ObjectEmitter, FunctionEmitter - Complex expressions\n- **Stencil Generation**: Produces a CompilationStencil containing bytecode, GC things, scope information, and other script metadata\n\n### 7. Intermediate Format: Stencil (js/src/frontend/Stencil.h/cpp)\nAfter bytecode emission, compilation data is organized into a Stencil structure:\n- **CompilationStencil** - Contains the complete compiled form of a script\n- **ExtensibleCompilationStencil** - Mutable stencil used during compilation\n- **Stencil Contents**: Bytecode bytes (jsbytecode*), GC things (functions, objects), scope information, try notes, source notes\n- **Format**: Can be serialized/deserialized (XDR) for caching and faster loading\n- **Instantiation**: The stencil is later instantiated into runtime objects when the script is loaded into a context\n\n### 8. Final Bytecode Output: JSScript (js/src/vm/JSScript.h/cpp)\nThe final compiled script object that represents executable JavaScript bytecode:\n- **JSScript Class** (js/src/vm/JSScript.h) - The canonical representation of compiled JavaScript code\n- **Structure**: Contains:\n  - Bytecode array (sequence of JSOp instructions and operands)\n  - Metadata: source location, function length, arguments count\n  - Scope chain information\n  - Try-catch-finally exception handling information\n  - Source notes for mapping bytecode back to source (debugging)\n  - GC thing references (inner functions, RegExps, etc.)\n- **Runtime Execution**: The bytecode interpreter (or JIT compiler) executes the bytecode stored in JSScript\n- **Relationship to Stencil**: JSScript is created from a CompilationStencil during instantiation\n\n### Complete Compilation Flow:\n\n1. **Input**: JavaScript source text (char16_t or UTF-8)\n2. **TokenStream**: Lexical analysis → tokens\n3. **Parser** (globalBody/evalBody): Syntax analysis → ParseNode AST\n4. **SharedContext**: Tracks scope and compilation state\n5. **BytecodeEmitter** (emitScript): AST traversal → JSOp bytecode instructions\n6. **Stencil**: Bytecode + metadata organization\n7. **JSScript**: Final executable bytecode object\n8. **Output**: Compiled script ready for execution\n\nThis architecture cleanly separates concerns: tokenization (lexing), parsing (syntax), and code generation (bytecode emission), with shared context maintaining information needed across phases."
